The mound faced westward, with a keyhole type and a single row of fukiishi and possibly three rows of haniwa around the posterior mound and one row on the anterior portion. A shallow surrounding ditch, irregular in depth, was also present. A vertical pit was dug in the center of the posterior mound to house a burial chamber made of stones, which likely contained a wooden coffin. Although looted in antiquity, small finds included a bronze nyūmonkyō mirror, a knife, an iron arrowhead, and fragments of Sue pottery and Haji pottery. The kofun is dated to the mid-5th century.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', p.30; Fujisawa Atsushi, "Uramachi Kofun", p.252.</ref>

== location ==
Uramachi Kofun was situated on the western edge of the Sendai Plain between the [[:en:Natori River|Natori River]] and the {{ill|Hirose River (Miyagi Prefecture)|ja|広瀬川 (宮城県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirose River (Miyagi Prefecture)|qq=}}, closer to the Natori River. Nearby, kofun of similar map_size include {{ill|Hitotsuzuka Kofun|ja|一塚古墳|1=Hitotsuka Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitotsuzuka Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitotsuka Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|ja|二塚古墳 (仙台市)|1=Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|lt=Futatsuzuka Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|13=User:Immanuelle/Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|qq=}}, as well as the larger {{ill|Kabutozuka Kofun (Sendai)|ja|兜塚古墳 (仙台市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kabutozuka Kofun (Sendai)|qq=}}. The region's largest kofun are the [[:en:Raijinyama Kofun|Raijinyama Kofun]] and [[:en:Tōmizuka Kofun|Tōmizuka Kofun]], located across the Natori and Hirose Rivers, respectively.

Uramachi Kofun was built on the southern edge of the Mikamine Hills, overlooking the lowlands. Viewed from below, the keyhole type would have appeared against the backdrop of the hills.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', p.17.</ref> Many similar Kofuns in the area were destroyed before receiving names or documentation.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', p.6.</ref>

== Excavation and Current Status ==
In 1949, the archaeologist Itō Nobuo observed the site, describing it as an overgrown mound surrounded by a cedar grove. At that time, Itō believed it to be a circular mound. By 1972, the area had been transtypeed into residential lots, and the grove had been cleared. A cultural property survey by the Sendai City Board of Education revealed the keyhole type. The mound was partially destroyed during construction and was entirely removed in 1973 following excavation.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', pp.1, 7-10.</ref>

