'''Uramachi Kofun''' (裏町古墳) was a {{ill|Zenpō-kōen-fun|en|Zenpō-kōen-fun|WD=Q11268718|lt=Zenpō-kōen-fun|1=Zenpō-kōen-fun}} located in Nishitaga 1-chome, Taihaku-ku, Sendai, Miyagi Prefecture. Constructed during the {{ill|Middle Kofun period|ja|古墳時代中期|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Middle Kofun period|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (5th century), the mound was approximately 40 meters in length, surrounded by {{ill|Fukiishi|en|Fukiishi|WD=Q11621213|lt=fukiishi|1=Fukiishi}} and cylindrical haniwa. burial goods such as a bronze mirror, knife, and iron arrowheads were excavated from a {{ill|pit-style burial chamber|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pit-style burial chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}}. The site was investigated in 1972 and 1973 before being destroyed in 1973.

== Overview ==
Uramachi Kofun was located at the base of the {{ill|Mikamine Hills|ja|三神峯丘陵|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikamine Hills|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, facing the southern part of the Sendai Plain. At the time of excavation, the site was within Tomizawa, Uramachi, Sendai City. However, after changes in the administrative district, it is now part of Nishitaga 1-chome, Taihaku-ku. The area was once dotted with small to medium-sized kofun, including Uramachi Kofun.

The mound faced westward, with a keyhole type and a single row of fukiishi and possibly three rows of haniwa around the posterior mound and one row on the anterior portion. A shallow surrounding ditch, irregular in depth, was also present. A vertical pit was dug in the center of the posterior mound to house a burial chamber made of stones, which likely contained a wooden coffin. Although looted in antiquity, small finds included a bronze nyūmonkyō mirror, a knife, an iron arrowhead, and fragments of Sue pottery and Haji pottery. The kofun is dated to the mid-5th century.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', p.30; Fujisawa Atsushi, "Uramachi Kofun", p.252.</ref>

== location ==
Uramachi Kofun was situated on the western edge of the Sendai Plain between the {{ill|Natori River|en|Natori River|WD=Q11414763|lt=Natori River|1=Natori River}} and the {{ill|Hirose River (Miyagi Prefecture)|ja|広瀬川 (宮城県)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirose River (Miyagi Prefecture)|1=Hirose River|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11485581}}, closer to the Natori River. Nearby, kofun of similar map_size include {{ill|Hitotsuzuka Kofun|ja|一塚古墳|1=Hitotsuka Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitotsuzuka Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitotsuka Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|ja|二塚古墳 (仙台市)|1=Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|lt=Futatsuzuka Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|13=User:Immanuelle/Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|qq=}}, as well as the larger {{ill|Kabutozuka Kofun (Sendai)|ja|兜塚古墳 (仙台市)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kabutozuka Kofun (Sendai)|qq=}}. The region's largest kofun are the {{ill|Raijinyama Kofun|en|Raijinyama Kofun|WD=Q11660187|lt=Raijinyama Kofun|1=Raijinyama Kofun}} and {{ill|Tōmizuka Kofun|en|Tōmizuka Kofun|WD=Q11642380|lt=Tōmizuka Kofun|1=Tōmizuka Kofun}}, located across the Natori and Hirose Rivers, respectively.

Uramachi Kofun was built on the southern edge of the Mikamine Hills, overlooking the lowlands. Viewed from below, the keyhole type would have appeared against the backdrop of the hills.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', p.17.</ref> Many similar Kofuns in the area were destroyed before receiving names or documentation.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', p.6.</ref>

== Excavation and Current Status ==
In 1949, the archaeologist Itō Nobuo observed the site, describing it as an overgrown mound surrounded by a cedar grove. At that time, Itō believed it to be a circular mound. By 1972, the area had been transtypeed into residential lots, and the grove had been cleared. A cultural property survey by the Sendai City Board of Education revealed the keyhole type. The mound was partially destroyed during construction and was entirely removed in 1973 following excavation.<ref>'Sendai City Tomizawa Uramachi Kofun Excavation Report', pp.1, 7-10.</ref>

